# Stream Processor Agent

`mn-agents.prototype.stream_processor` consumes an ordered, finite iterable one
item at a time. For every item it processes, emits, and then checkpoints. The
whole item pipeline may be retried, with either fail-fast or collected errors.

Use it when source order and “checkpoint only after successful emission” matter
more than parallel throughput.

## Quick start

```python
from mn_prototype_stream_processor_agent import (
    StreamProcessorSpec,
    create_agent,
)


processor = create_agent(
    StreamProcessorSpec(
        source=lambda context, **_: context["frames"],
        item_id=lambda frame: frame["id"],
        process=lambda _context, frame, **_: frame["pixels"].hex(),
        emit=lambda context, frame, value, **_: context["sink"].append(
            {"id": frame["id"], "encoded": value}
        ),
        checkpoint=lambda context, frame, _value, **_: context[
            "checkpoint"
        ].update({"last_frame": frame["id"]}),
        retries=2,
        failure_policy="collect",
    )
)
summary = processor(context)
```

## Processing order

For each item:

```text
process -> emit -> checkpoint -> record processed
```

Checkpoint never runs before a successful emit. Items are fully resolved in
source order, and no later item starts while the current item is retrying.

## Retry warning

A retry repeats `process`, `emit`, and `checkpoint` as one unit. If `emit`
succeeds but `checkpoint` fails, retrying can emit the item again. Make process,
emit, and checkpoint idempotent or add deduplication in the injected adapters.

Use `entity_queue` instead when bounded parallel processing and skip semantics
are needed. Use `supervised_service` when the source is open-ended or polled
over time.

See [SPEC.md](SPEC.md) for exact failure and summary behavior.
